Dear all,=20

This is a standard fact, proved for instance in details in "Categories =
for the Working Mathematician" (Chapter 4, Section 4, Theorem 1 in the =
second edition), that a functor is an equivalence of categories if and =
only if it is part of an adjoint equivalence. I would like to use the =
fact that this is true in an arbitrary 2-category, i.e. that given an =
equivalence in a 2-category the invertible 2-cells can be required to =
satisfy the triangle identities. Is there a standard reference for this =
fact? Well-known books such as classical introductions to category =
theory are particularly welcome.=20

Thanks,=20

Jonathan=


